#slide[
  == Generated subgroups

  #definition("Subgroup generated by a subset")[
    Let $S subset.eq G$. The subgroup "generated" by $S$ is the smallest subgroup of $G$ that contains $S$. We denote it by $chevron.l S chevron.r$.

    More precisely, $ chevron.l S chevron.r := inter.big_(H <= G, S subset.eq H) H $
  ]

  This is similar to the concept of "span" in linear algebra.
]
#slide[
  #theorem("Another definition of the subgroup generated by a subset")[

    Let $S subset.eq G$. Then $chevron.l S chevron.r$ is the set of all finite products of elements of $S$ and their inverses. More precisely, let $overline(S) = {s_1 s_2 ... s_n | n in NN, s_i in S "or" s_i in S^(-1)}$, then $chevron.l S chevron.r = overline(S)$.
  ]
  If you are still familiar with linear algebra, recall that the span of a set of vectors is also the set of all linear combinations of the vectors in the set. The concepts are similar.
  #proof[
    First, use the subgroup criterion to show that $overline(S) <= G$.

    Then verify that $chevron.l S chevron.r = overline(S)$:

    - $chevron.l S chevron.r <= overline(S)$: because $overline(S)$ is a subgroup containing $S$.
    - $overline(S) <= chevron.l S chevron.r$: observe that each element of $overline(S)$ is a finite product of elements of $S$ and their inverses.
  ]
]

